{"title_page": "\u00c9ric Heulot", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = \u00c9ric Heulot\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1962|10|9|df=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Rennes]], France\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n| updated       = \n}}\n\n'''\u00c9ric Heulot''' (born 9 October 1962) is a French former [[Cycle sport|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|team time trial]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/eric-heulot-1.html |title=Eric Heulot Olympic Results |accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heulot, Eric}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rennes]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = \u00c9ric Heulot\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1962|10|9|df=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Rennes]], France\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n| updated       = \n}}\n\n'''\u00c9ric Heulot''' (born 9 October 1962) is a French former [[Cycle sport|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|team time trial]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/eric-heulot-1.html |title=Eric Heulot Olympic Results |accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heulot, Eric}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rennes]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89ric_Heulot"}
{"title_page": "J. David Simons", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n | name        = J. David Simons\n | image       = J David Simons Book Launch 2011.JPG\n | birth_name   = Jonathan David Simons\n | birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1953|08|27|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n | death_date  = \n | death_place = \n | occupation  = \n | nationality = UK\n | website     = {{URL|http://www.jdavidsimons.com}}\n}}\n\n'''J. David Simons''' (born 27 August 1953) is a [[Scottish writers|Scottish novelist]] and short story writer.  He was educated at [[Hutchesons' Grammar School|Hutchesons' Boys Grammar School]] and graduated with a law degree from [[Glasgow University]] in 1973. He worked as a lawyer in Edinburgh, a cotton farmer on [[Kibbutz]] [[Ashdot Ya'akov]] Ichud in Israel, a charity administrator for the Cyrenians  in West London, a university lecturer at [[Keio University]], Japan, and a journalist for multi-national publishing house [[Informa]], before returning to his native [[Glasgow]] in 2006 to pursue his career as a writer.<ref name=bold19>{{cite web |author=Amanda McCall |url=http://news.stv.tv/west-central/98186-theres-no-place-like-home-for-author-j-david-simons/ |title=There's no place like home for author J. David Simons &#124; Glasgow & West |publisher=News |date=2012-05-05 |accessdate=2014-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233848/http://news.stv.tv/west-central/98186-theres-no-place-like-home-for-author-j-david-simons/ |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Literary career ==\nSimons' first novel ''The Credit Draper'' was published by [[Two Ravens Press]] in May 2008 and was shortlisted for the [[McKitterick Prize]] in June 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/prizes-2009 |title=Prizes 2009 &#124; Society of Authors - Protecting the rights and furthering the interests of authors |publisher=Society of Authors |date=2009-06-18 |accessdate=2014-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924103753/http://www.societyofauthors.org/prizes-2009 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This novel is set primarily within the [[History of the Jews in Scotland|Glasgow Jewish Community]] in the early part of the 20th century<ref>\"The Credit Draper\" - An Interview with J. David Simons, The Herald Scotland, 31 May 2008.</ref> and represents the first part of his \"Glasgow to Galilee\" trilogy. Simons goes on to tackle issues of socialism, feminism and birth control in Glasgow during the 1920s in his second novel in this trilogy - ''The Liberation of Celia Kahn''<ref name=bold19/> - which was published by [[Five Leaves Publications]] in February 2011 along with a re-print of ''The Credit Draper''.  His third novel ''An Exquisite Sense of What is Beautiful'' set in Japan was published by Saraband in March 2013 and examines the theme of denial, especially in regard to the dropping of the atomic bombs on [[Hiroshima]] and [[Nagasaki]] by the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9olqzYMl8Xs |title=An Exquisite Sense of What Is Beautiful |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2014-06-17}}</ref> In ''The Land Agent'', the third novel in the \"Glasgow to Galilee\" trilogy, published by Saraband in October 2014, Simons turns his attention to 1920s Palestine and the conflict over a strategic piece of land that doesn't exist on any map.<ref>A Special Request - a novel extract from The Land Agent, The Scotsman, 18 October 2014.</ref> Simons' fifth novel ''A Woman of Integrity'' was originally published in March 2017 by Freight before its rights were acquired by Saraband. The novel deals with the lives of two film actresses from different eras trying to carve out careers for themselves away from the shadows of men. Apart from his fiction writing, Simons is also a mentor for the [[Scottish Book Trust]] and an editor with the Blue Pencil Agency.\n\n== Awards and Grants ==\n\n* Writer's Bursary - Scottish Arts Council, September 2009<ref>http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/resources/publications/past_awards/pdf/Past%20Awards%20September%202009.pdf</ref>\n*[[Robert Louis Stevenson Fellowship]], June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.stv.tv/scotland/244752-scottish-writers-awarded-coveted-robert-louis-stevenson-fellowship/ |title=Scottish writers awarded coveted Robert Louis Stevenson Fellowship &#124; Scotland |publisher=News |date=2011-04-22 |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n*Grant from the [[Society of Authors]] Foundation, September 2012. \n*Talent Development Award - [[Creative Scotland]], March 2013<ref>http://www.creativescotland.com/__data/assets/excel_doc/0005/25295/Awards-Made-March-2013.xls</ref>\n*Open Project Funding Award - [[Creative Scotland]], July 2015<ref>http://www.creativescotland.com/funding/latest-information/awards-listing/2015/Awards-Made-July-2015-v2.xlsx{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Published Work ==\n\n=== Novels ===\n*''The Credit Draper'' (Two Ravens Press 2008, re-printed Five Leaves 2011, re-printed Saraband 2014)\n*''The Liberation of Celia Kahn'' (Five Leaves 2011, reprinted Saraband 2014)\n*''An Exquisite Sense of What is Beautiful'' (Saraband 2013)\n*''The Land Agent'' (Saraband 2014)\n*''A Woman of Integrity'' (Freight 2017, re-printed Saraband 2018)\n\n=== Short Stories ===\n* ''The Lovebirds'' (Printed Matter 1993)\n* ''Soundscapes'' (Printed Matter 1995)\n* ''Maimonides'' (London Magazine 2000)\n* ''The Custodian'' (Gutter Magazine 2011)\n* ''Poland 1919 - Decisions, Decisions'' (Spilling Ink 2011)\n* ''Poland 1919 - Palestine or America'' (Glasgow University Press 2012)\n* ''The Coffee Kid'' (runner-up in the Poetic Republic Short Story Competition 2015)<ref>http://www.poeticrepublic.com/news/29/the-final-shortlist-for-the-poetic-republic-short-story-competition-/</ref>\n* ''The Myth of Bert Slater'' (Nutmeg Magazine Issue, No 2, 2017)\n* ''Remember From Where You Came'' (With Their Best Clothes On, New Writing Scotland 36, 2018)\n* ''The Responsibility of Love'' (Lakeview International Journal of Literature and Arts, 2019)\n\n=== Essays ===\n* ''Kibbutz - The Golden Years'' (appearing in Utopia, Five Leaves 2012)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.jdavidsimons.com Author's website]\n*[http://www.saraband.net Publisher's website - Saraband]\n*[http://www.fiveleaves.co.uk Publisher's website - Five Leaves]\n*[http://www.thejc.com/arts/books/5827/review-the-credit-draper Review of The Credit Draper - The Jewish Chronicle]\n*[http://historicalnovelsociety.org/reviews/the-liberation-of-celia-kahn/ Review of The Liberation of Celia Kahn - Historical Novel Society]\n*[http://www.heraldscotland.com/books-poetry/reviews/j-david-simons-an-exquisite-sense-of-what-is-beautiful-saraband.20820013 Review of An Exquisite Sense of What is Beautiful - Herald Scotland]\n*[http://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2014/11/the-land-agent-an-evening-with-j-david-simons/ Review of The Land Agent - The Edinburgh Reporter]\n*[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15162546.__39_Soul-searching_tales_of_women_propelled_by_moral_dilemmas__39_/ Review of A Woman of Integrity - Herald Scotland]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simons, J. David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Scottish short story writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:British Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hutchesons' Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n | name        = J. David Simons\n | image       = J David Simons Book Launch 2011.JPG\n | birth_name   = Jonathan David Simons\n | birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1953|08|27|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n | death_date  = \n | death_place = \n | occupation  = \n | nationality = UK\n | website     = {{URL|http://www.jdavidsimons.com}}\n}}\n\n'''J. David Simons''' (born 27 August 1953) is a [[Scottish writers|Scottish novelist]] and short story writer.  He was educated at [[Hutchesons' Grammar School|Hutchesons' Boys Grammar School]] and graduated with a law degree from [[Glasgow University]] in 1973. He worked as a lawyer in Edinburgh, a cotton farmer on [[Kibbutz]] [[Ashdot Ya'akov]] Ichud in Israel, a charity administrator for the Cyrenians  in West London, a university lecturer at [[Keio University]], Japan, and a journalist for multi-national publishing house [[Informa]], before returning to his native [[Glasgow]] in 2006 to pursue his career as a writer.<ref name=bold19>{{cite web |author=Amanda McCall |url=http://news.stv.tv/west-central/98186-theres-no-place-like-home-for-author-j-david-simons/ |title=There's no place like home for author J. David Simons &#124; Glasgow & West |publisher=News |date=2012-05-05 |accessdate=2014-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233848/http://news.stv.tv/west-central/98186-theres-no-place-like-home-for-author-j-david-simons/ |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Literary career ==\nSimons' first novel ''The Credit Draper'' was published by [[Two Ravens Press]] in May 2008 and was shortlisted for the [[McKitterick Prize]] in June 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/prizes-2009 |title=Prizes 2009 &#124; Society of Authors - Protecting the rights and furthering the interests of authors |publisher=Society of Authors |date=2009-06-18 |accessdate=2014-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924103753/http://www.societyofauthors.org/prizes-2009 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This novel is set primarily within the [[History of the Jews in Scotland|Glasgow Jewish Community]] in the early part of the 20th century<ref>\"The Credit Draper\" - An Interview with J. David Simons, The Herald Scotland, 31 May 2008.</ref> and represents the first part of his \"Glasgow to Galilee\" trilogy. Simons goes on to tackle issues of socialism, feminism and birth control in Glasgow during the 1920s in his second novel in this trilogy - ''The Liberation of Celia Kahn''<ref name=bold19/> - which was published by [[Five Leaves Publications]] in February 2011 along with a re-print of ''The Credit Draper''.  His third novel ''An Exquisite Sense of What is Beautiful'' set in Japan was published by Saraband in March 2013 and examines the theme of denial, especially in regard to the dropping of the atomic bombs on [[Hiroshima]] and [[Nagasaki]] by the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9olqzYMl8Xs |title=An Exquisite Sense of What Is Beautiful |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2014-06-17}}</ref> In ''The Land Agent'', the third novel in the \"Glasgow to Galilee\" trilogy, published by Saraband in October 2014, Simons turns his attention to 1920s Palestine and the conflict over a strategic piece of land that doesn't exist on any map.<ref>A Special Request - a novel extract from The Land Agent, The Scotsman, 18 October 2014.</ref> Simons' fifth novel ''A Woman of Integrity'' was originally published in March 2017 by Freight before its rights were acquired by Saraband. The novel deals with the lives of two film actresses from different eras trying to carve out careers for themselves away from the shadows of men. Apart from his fiction writing, Simons is also a mentor for the [[Scottish Book Trust]] and an editor with the Blue Pencil Agency.\n\n== Awards and Grants ==\n\n* Writer's Bursary - Scottish Arts Council, September 2009<ref>http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/resources/publications/past_awards/pdf/Past%20Awards%20September%202009.pdf</ref>\n*[[Robert Louis Stevenson Fellowship]], June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.stv.tv/scotland/244752-scottish-writers-awarded-coveted-robert-louis-stevenson-fellowship/ |title=Scottish writers awarded coveted Robert Louis Stevenson Fellowship &#124; Scotland |publisher=News |date=2011-04-22 |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n*Grant from the [[Society of Authors]] Foundation, September 2012. \n*Talent Development Award - [[Creative Scotland]], March 2013<ref>http://www.creativescotland.com/__data/assets/excel_doc/0005/25295/Awards-Made-March-2013.xls</ref>\n*Open Project Funding Award - [[Creative Scotland]], July 2015<ref>http://www.creativescotland.com/funding/latest-information/awards-listing/2015/Awards-Made-July-2015-v2.xlsx{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Published Work ==\n\n=== Novels ===\n*''The Credit Draper'' (Two Ravens Press 2008, re-printed Five Leaves 2011, re-printed Saraband 2014)\n*''The Liberation of Celia Kahn'' (Five Leaves 2011, reprinted Saraband 2014)\n*''An Exquisite Sense of What is Beautiful'' (Saraband 2013)\n*''The Land Agent'' (Saraband 2014)\n*''A Woman of Integrity'' (Freight 2017, re-printed Saraband 2018)\n\n=== Short Stories ===\n* ''The Lovebirds'' (Printed Matter 1993)\n* ''Soundscapes'' (Printed Matter 1995)\n* ''Maimonides'' (London Magazine 2000)\n* ''The Custodian'' (Gutter Magazine 2011)\n* ''Poland 1919 - Decisions, Decisions'' (Spilling Ink 2011)\n* ''Poland 1919 - Palestine or America'' (Glasgow University Press 2012)\n* ''The Coffee Kid'' (runner-up in the Poetic Republic Short Story Competition 2015)<ref>http://www.poeticrepublic.com/news/29/the-final-shortlist-for-the-poetic-republic-short-story-competition-/</ref>\n* ''The Myth of Bert Slater'' (Nutmeg Magazine Issue, No 2, 2017)\n* ''Remember From Where You Came'' (With Their Best Clothes On, New Writing Scotland 36, 2018)\n\n=== Essays ===\n* ''Kibbutz - The Golden Years'' (appearing in Utopia, Five Leaves 2012)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.jdavidsimons.com Author's website]\n*[http://www.saraband.net Publisher's website - Saraband]\n*[http://www.fiveleaves.co.uk Publisher's website - Five Leaves]\n*[http://www.thejc.com/arts/books/5827/review-the-credit-draper Review of The Credit Draper - The Jewish Chronicle]\n*[http://historicalnovelsociety.org/reviews/the-liberation-of-celia-kahn/ Review of The Liberation of Celia Kahn - Historical Novel Society]\n*[http://www.heraldscotland.com/books-poetry/reviews/j-david-simons-an-exquisite-sense-of-what-is-beautiful-saraband.20820013 Review of An Exquisite Sense of What is Beautiful - Herald Scotland]\n*[http://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2014/11/the-land-agent-an-evening-with-j-david-simons/ Review of The Land Agent - The Edinburgh Reporter]\n*[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15162546.__39_Soul-searching_tales_of_women_propelled_by_moral_dilemmas__39_/ Review of A Woman of Integrity - Herald Scotland]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simons, J. David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Scottish short story writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:British Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hutchesons' Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n", "name_user": "Judesimo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._David_Simons"}
{"title_page": "\u00c9ric Guyot", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = \u00c9ric Guyot\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1962|3|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Belfort]], [[France]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''\u00c9ric Guyot''' (born 10 March 1962) is a French former professional [[cycle sport|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/Eric_Guyot |title=\u00c9ric Guyot |accessdate=3 April 2015 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> He rode in one edition of the [[Tour de France]] and four editions of the [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|9540}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guyot, Eric}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belfort]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = \u00c9ric Guyot\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1962|3|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Belfort]], [[France]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1    