hmiadzin Cathedral]] on the background of [[Mount Ararat]]\n| [[Noah]], his family members and animals on the background of [[Mount Ararat]]\n|-\n| [[File:1000 dram 2018 Obverse.jpg|300px|]]  \n| [[File:1000 dram 2018 Reverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| 1,000 {{Armenian dram}}\n| \n| Violet\n| [[Paruyr Sevak]], poems\n| Paryur Sevak house (museum), Zangakatun; statue of Sevak \n|-\n| [[File:2000 dram 2018 Obverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| [[File:2000 dram 2018 Reverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| 2,000 {{Armenian dram}}\n| \n| Brown\n| [[Tigran Petrosian]], chessboard\n| Tigran Petrosyan Chess House (Yerevan), statue of Petrosyan\n|-\n| [[File:5000 dram 2018 Obverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| [[File:5000 dram 2018 Reverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| 5,000 {{Armenian dram}}\n| \n| Red\n| [[William Saroyan]], covers from Saroyan's books, mountain\n| Statue of Saroyan (Yerevan) \n|-\n| [[File:10000 dram 2018 Obverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| [[File:10000 dram 2018 Reverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| 10,000 {{Armenian dram}}\n| \n| Purple \n| [[Komitas]]\n| Gevorkian Seminary and statue of Komitas, Vagharshapat (Etchmiadzin)\n|-\n|[[File:20000 dram 2018 Obverse.jpg|300px|]]\n|[[File:20000 dram 2018 Reverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| 20,000 {{Armenian dram}}\n| \n| Blue\n| [[Ivan Aivazovsky]]\n| Art Museum and statue of Aivazovskiy, Feodosia (Crimea)\n|-\n| [[File:50000 dram 2018 Obverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| [[File:50000 dram 2018 Reverse.jpg|300px|]]\n| 50,000 {{Armenian dram}}\n| \n| Gold\n| [[Gregory the Illuminator|Saint Gregory the Illuminator]], manuscripts telling the life of St. Gregory, images of the dome of the Mother Cathedral of Holy Etchmiadzin and the winged cross\n| Khor Virap monastery (Chapel of St. Gregory), Ararat Plain, tombstone of St. Gregory the Illuminator (Etchmiadzin), statue of St. Gregory the Illuminator\n|-\n|}\n\n==Exchange rates==\nThe modern dram came into effect on 22 November 1993, at a rate of 200 [[Russian ruble|rubles]] = 1 dram (1 [[United States dollar|USD]] : 404 AMD). The dram is not pegged to any currency other than the [[Artsakh dram]].\n\n{{Exchange Rate|AMD|RUB|note=Rates obtained from these websites may be slightly different from the rates the Central Bank of Armenia publishes}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Artsakh dram]]\n*[[Economy of Armenia]]\n*[[List of currencies]]\n*[[List of currencies in Europe]]\n*[[List of circulating currencies]]\n{{clear}}\n{{Portal bar|Money|Economics|Numismatics}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Money of Armenia}}\n* [https://www.cba.am/ Central Bank of Armenia]\n* [http://ratepredict.info/ Central Bank of Armenia next day USD to AMD exchange rate prediction Engine]\n* [http://www.armeniapedia.org/index.php?title=Armenian_Dram_Sign Armenian Dram Sign] History, shape, and promotion of Armenian Dram Sign\n* [http://worldcoingallery.com/countries/Armenia.php Coin Types from Armenia] Lists, pictures, and values of Armenian coin types\n* {{CISCoins|Armenia}}\n* [http://www.bis-ans-ende-der-welt.net/Armenien-B-En.htm The banknotes of Armenia] {{in lang|en|de}}\n\n{{Currencies of Asia}}\n{{Currencies of Europe}}\n{{Currencies of post-Soviet states}}\n{{Armenia topics}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of Armenia]]\n[[Category:Currencies introduced in 1993]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|earlier Armenian currency|Armenian ruble}}\n{{Infobox currency\n| currency_name_in_local = {{native name|hy|\u0540\u0561\u0575\u056f\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0534\u0580\u0561\u0574|italic=no}}\n| image_1 = 100,000 Armenian dram - 2009 (obverse).jpg\n| image_title_1 = A 100,000 (haryur hazar) Armenian dram banknote, the highest denominated banknote in circulation.\n| no_plural = Y\n| iso_code = AMD\n| iso_number = 051\n| using_countries = {{flag|Armenia}}<br />{{flag|Artsakh}}\n| inflation_rate = 2.7% (Armenia only)\n| inflation_source_date = ''[https://www.cba.am/en/sitepages/default.aspx]'', January 2018\n| subunit_ratio_1 = 1/100\n| subunit_name_1 = luma (\u056c\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0561)\n| symbol = {{Armenian dram}} (\u058f) or \u0564\u0580.\n| frequently_used_coins = 10\u058f, 20\u058f, 50\u058f, 100\u058f, 200\u058f, 500\u058f\n| rarely_used_coins= 10, 20, 50 luma, 1\u058f, 3\u058f, 5\u058f\n| frequently_used_banknotes = 1000\u058f, 5000\u058f, 10,000\u058f, 20,000\u058f, 50,000\u058f, 100,000\u058f\n| rarely_used_banknotes = 50\u058f, 100\u058f, 500\u058f, 2000\u058f\n| issuing_authority = [[Central Bank of Armenia|Central Bank of the Republic of Armenia]]\n| issuing_authority_website = {{URL|www.cba.am}}\n| pegged_with = [[Artsakh dram]]\n}}\n\nThe '''dram''' ({{lang-hy|'''\u0564\u0580\u0561\u0574'''}}; [[Armenian dram sign|sign]]: \u058f; [[ISO 4217|code]]: '''AMD''') is the [[monetary unit]] of [[Armenia]] and the neighboring unrecognized [[Republic of Artsakh]] (Nagorno-Karabakh). It was historically subdivided into 100 '''luma''' ({{lang-hy|[[wikt:\u056c\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0561|\u056c\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0561]]}}). The word \"dram\" translates into English as \"money\" and is cognate with the Greek [[drachma]] and the Arabic [[dirham]], as well as the English weight unit [[Dram (unit)|dram]]. The first instance of a dram currency was in the period from 1199 to 1375, when silver coins called dram were issued.\n\n== History ==\nOn 21 September 1991, a national referendum proclaimed [[Armenia]] as a republic independent from the [[Soviet Union]]. The [[Central Bank of Armenia]], established on 27 March 1993, was given the exclusive right of issuing the national currency.\n\nIn the immediate aftermath of the [[collapse of the Soviet Union]] attempts were made to maintain a common currency (the [[ruble|Russian ruble]]) among [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]] states. Armenia joined this ruble zone. However it soon became clear that maintaining a [[currency union]] in the unstable political and economical circumstances of the post-Soviet states would be very difficult. The ruble zone effectively collapsed with the unilateral [[monetary reform in Russia, 1993]]. As result the states that were still participating ([[Kazakhstan]], [[Uzbekistan]], [[Turkmenistan]], [[Moldova]], Armenia and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) were 'pushed out' and forced to introduce separate currencies.  \nArmenia was one of the last countries to do so when it introduced the dram on 22 November 1993.<ref>Pomfret, Richard (2001). The IMF and the Ruble zone. Available at: http://www.readcube.com/articles/10.1057/ces.2002.17</ref>\n\n=== Armenian dram sign ===\n{{main|Armenian dram sign}}\n[[File:dramsign-oiriginal-idea.jpg|thumb|100px|left|The dram Sign]]\n\nAfter its proclamation of independence, [[Armenia]] put into circulation its own national currency, the Armenian Dram; this required a monetary sign. As the result of common business practice and the unique pattern of Armenian letters, the shape of the sign and its variations appeared in the business scratches (daybooks). Until the official endorsement of the sign a number of artists and businessmen developed and offered various shapes for it. Now the dram symbol is included in the Armenian standard for the national characters and symbols and in the Armenian computer fonts. The current standard sign for the Armenian dram (<span style=' font-family: \"Segoe UI Semilight\", inherit '>\u058f</span>, image: {{Armenian dram}}; {{lang-hy|'''\u0534\u0580\u0561\u0574'''}}; [[ISO 4217|code]]: AMD) was designed in 1995. In Unicode, it is encoded at {{unichar|058f|ARMENIAN DRAM SIGN|html=}}.\n\n==Coins==\nIn 1994, a first series of aluminium coins was introduced in denominations of 10, 20 and 50 luma, 1, 3, 5 and 10 dram. \nIn 2003 and 2004, a second series consisting of 10, 20, 50, 100, 200 and 500 dram coins was introduced to replace the first series.\n\nThe Central Bank has also issued a great number of commemorative coins intended for sale to collectors. A listing can be found at the authorized central bank distributors.<ref>[https://www.cba.am/en/SitePages/nccommemorativecoins.aspx  Armenian commemorative coins for sale]</ref><ref>[http://arm-moneti.blogspot.nl/ Armenian commemorative coins cathalogue]</ref>\n\n===First series (1994-2002)===\nIn 1994, a first series of aluminium coins was introduced in denominations of 10, 20 and 50 luma, 1, 3, 5 and 10 dram. The other coins are officially in circulation but rarely used because of their low nominal value.<ref>BBC (2013). Available at: https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-21572359</ref><ref>Armenian Central Bank. www.cba.am</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n!colspan=\"13\"|First series (1994)\n|- \n! colspan=\"2\"| Image !!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!colspan=\"3\"| Technical parameters !! colspan=\"3\" | Description\n|- \n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Diameter !! Mass !! Composition !! Edge !! Obverse !! Reverse \n|-\n| [[File:AM 1994 averse.png|200px]]\n| [[File:AM 1994 10 luma.png|200px]] \n| 10 luma<ref>Central Bank of Armenia. Available at: https://www.cba.am/en/SitePages/detailsnccracoinsnotcirculated.aspx?nominal=1</ref>\n| 16&nbsp;mm\n| 0.6 g\n|rowspan=\"7\"| [[Aluminium]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"| Smooth\n|rowspan=\"7\"| [[Coat of arms of Armenia|Armenian coat of arms]]\n|rowspan=\"7\"| Value, year of minting\n|-\n| [[File:AM 1994 averse.png|200px]]\n| [[File:AM 1994 20 luma.png|200px]]\n| 20 luma<ref>Central Bank of Armenia. Available at: https://www.cba.am/en/SitePages/detailsnccracoinsnotcirculated.aspx?nominal=2</ref>\n| 18&nbsp;mm\n| 0.75 g\n|-\n| [[File:AM 1994 averse.png|200px]]\n| [[File:AM 1994 50 luma.png|200px]]\n| 50 luma<ref>Central Bank of Armenia. Available at: https://www.cba.am/en/SitePages/detailsnccracoinsnotcirculated.aspx?nominal=3</ref>\n| 20&nbsp;mm\n| 0.95 g\n|- \n| [[File:AM 1994 averse.png|200px]]\n| [[File:AM 1994 1 dram.png|200px]]\n| 1{{Armenian dram}}<ref>Central Bank of Armenia. Available at: https://www.cba.am/en/SitePages/detailsnccracoinsnotcirculated.aspx?nominal=4</ref>\n| 22&nbsp;mm\n| 1.4 g\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Reeded\n|- \n| [[File:AM 1994 averse.png|200px]]\n| [[File:AM 1994 3 dram.png|20